Certain jus ad bellum criteria have, at their philosophical
roots, drawn from principles that have been developed as part of the Just War Tradition.182
These principles have included:
• a competent authority to order the war for a public purpose;
• a just cause (such as self-defense);
• the means must be proportionate to the just cause;
• all peaceful alternatives must have been exhausted; and
• a right intention on the part of the just belligerent.183
These principles may be reflected in modern law of war rules.

